# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Subject types:
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# feat: Add new user registration flow
# fix: Correct critical bug in login redirection
# chore: Update project dependencies to latest versions
# docs: Improve API endpoint documentation
# style: Refactor CSS for consistent button styling
# refactor: Consolidate redundant data fetching logic
# test: Add unit tests for authentication service
# build: Configure CI/CD pipeline for deployment
# ci: Update GitHub Actions workflow for pull requests
# perf: Optimize database queries for user data retrieval
# revert: Revert "feat: Implement experimental feature X"
#
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Commit message format guidelines:
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Subject line (first line):
# - Use imperative mood (e.g., "Add", "Fix", "Update")
# - Capitalized and no period at the end
# - Max 50 characters including prefix (feat:, fix:, etc.)
# - Leave a blank line after the subject line
#
# Body (optional, wrap at 72 chars):
# - Explain what was changed and why, not how
# - Provide additional context or motivation if necessary
# - Usually write plain text; avoid using bullets in the body
# - Leave a blank line between body and footer (if footer present)
# - Use proper sentences and end with periods
#
# Footer (optional):
# - Use for referencing issues, breaking changes, or co-authors
# - No bullets needed here, just plain lines like:
#     Closes: #123
#     Fixes: ABC-456
#     Co-authored-by: Name <email@example.com>
# - Do NOT end footer lines with a period
#
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Example commit message using this template:
#
# refactor: Consolidate redundant data fetching logic
#
# Combined duplicate API calls in user and product services to reduce
# network overhead and improve performance by 20%.
#
# Closes: #42
# Co-authored-by: Jane Doe <jane@example.com>
#
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Inspired by Chris Beams' guide on writing great Git commit messages
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
